e, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Liz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from Liz in Lugo province, Galicia (Spain). As a Hispanic name it may also be an altered form of   Lis  . Compare   Deliz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Stanislaw, Wladyslaw, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignatius, Malgorzata, Slawomir, Tadeusz, Tomasz, Boleslaw, Bronislaw, Darek.","Polish, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish and Czech dialect <i>lis</i> ‘fox’, Upper Sorbian <i>lis</i> ‘he-fox’, a nickname for a cunning person or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name. The presumably cognate Sorbian surname <b>Liš</b> is found in Germanized and probably also Americanized forms, only (see   Liesch   and   Lish  ). Compare also   Lese  ,   Lies  , and   Liss  .","Czech: nickname for a man with a bald pate, from a variant of the adjective <i>lysý</i> ‘bald’."]}]},{"name":"Rowland","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roland  , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that given name in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Roland","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. In Old French literature it is borne by a legendary Frankish hero, a vassal of Charlemagne, whose exploits are told in the <i>Chanson de Roland</i>. The subject of the poem is Roland's death at the Battle of Roncesvalles in the Pyrenees in  778 , while protecting the rearguard of the Frankish army on its retreat from Spain. Roland is depicted in literature and legend as headstrong and impulsive. His devoted friendship with the prudent  Oliver  is also legendary."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Rowland de Saint Liz was born about 1325, in Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Rowland de Saint Liz, was 29 and his mother, Agnes Empingham, was 21. He had at least 2 daughters with Alice Sarsonne de Pinchbeck. He died in 1429, at the age of 105."},"et":{"About 1325–1429":"umbes 1325–1429","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1355–1436":"1355–1436","1357–Female":"1357–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","About 1325":"umbes 1325","1330":"1330","Abt 1357":"umbes 1357","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1436":"1436","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1429":"1429","1328":"1328","Cottesmore, Rutland, England":"Cottesmore, Rutland, England","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"About 1325–1429":"noin 1325–1429","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1355–1436":"1355–1436","1357–Female":"1357–Kuollut","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1305–Female":"1305–Kuollut","About 1325":"noin 1325","1330":"1330","Abt 1357":"noin 1357","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1436":"1436","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1429":"1429","1328":"1328","Cottesmore, Rutland, England":"Cottesmore, Rutland, England","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"About 1325–1429":"environ 1325–1429","1325–1429":"1325–1429","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1355–1436":"1355–1436","1357–Female":"1357–Décédée","1298–Male":"1298–Décédé","1305–Female":"1305–Décédée","About 1325":"environ 1325","1330":"1330","Abt 1357":"environ 1357","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1436":"1436","1325":"1325","1357":"1357","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1429":"1429","1328":"1328","Cottesmore, Rutland, England":"Cottesmore, Rutland, Angleterre","Warkworth, Northamptonshire, England":"Warkworth, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Rowland de Saint Liz est né environ 1325, à Warkworth, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, son père, Rowland de Saint Liz, avait 29 ans et sa mère, Agnes Empingham, avait 21 ans. Il a eu au moins 2 filles avec Alice Sarsonne de Pinchbeck. Il est décédé en 1429, à l’âg